      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the mince",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{rapeseed-oil}} of oil in a large casserole over high heat. Add {{beef-mince}} of mince in two or three batches, leaving space between pieces. Cook without stirring for 3 minutes per batch until deeply browned, then break up. Transfer browned mince to a bowl.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the aromatics and spices",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Reduce the heat to medium. Cook {{onion}} diced onions in the same pan for 10 minutes until softened and beginning to colour. Add {{garlic}} of chopped garlic and cook 2 minutes. Add {{chilli-powder}} of chilli powder, {{cumin-ground}} of cumin, {{paprika-smoked}} of smoked paprika, {{coriander-ground}} of coriander and {{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée; stir and cook for 2 minutes until fragrant.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Simmer and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Return the browned mince to the pan. Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes, {{kidney-beans}} of kidney beans and {{stock-beef}} of beef stock. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Bring to a simmer, then cook on low heat for 40 to 45 minutes until the sauce is thick and the meat is tender. In the last 5 minutes, stir in {{dark-chocolate}} of dark chocolate if using; it deepens the flavour without adding sweetness.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Brown the mince in batches; crowding the pan causes steaming. Cook the dry spices in the fat for 2 minutes before adding liquid.",
              "cause": "Mince steamed rather than browned, or spices added without cooking them out.",
              "symptom": "Flat, grey flavour"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Taste before the beans go in and adjust. Stir in a spoonful of soured cream to cool a batch that's too hot.",
              "cause": "Over-seasoned with chilli powder, which varies widely in heat.",
              "symptom": "Chilli too hot to eat"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Simmer uncovered or with the lid slightly ajar. The chilli should reduce to a thick, coating consistency.",
              "cause": "Lid on during simmering, trapping steam.",
              "symptom": "Watery, thin sauce"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Chilli is the weeknight staple of the British as much as the American home. It is forgiving, cheap, better the second day, and serves cheerfully from a pot on the hob without ceremony. Serve over rice with soured cream, or in baked potatoes, or on nachos if it's that kind of evening.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
